'''Yael Stone''' (born 6 March 1985) is an Australian [[actress]]. She has worked extensively in Australian theatre and has won two [[Sydney Theatre Awards]]. Outside of Australian theatre, she is best known for her portrayal of [[Lorna Morello]] in the [[Netflix]] series ''[[Orange Is the New Black]]''. Stone is also known for her support of abortion rights and has vocally advocated for women's issues.

==Early life and education==
Stone was born and raised in [[Sydney]], the daughter of Judy, a nurse, and Harry Stone, an architect.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.thesaturdaypaper.com.au/culture/theatre/2015/05/02/the-kooky-life-orange-the-new-blacks-yael-stone/14304888001814 |title=The 'kooky' life of Orange Is the New Black's Yael Stone |first=Michaela |last=McGuire |date=2 May 2015 |publisher=}}</ref> Her father was born in [[Czechoslovakia]], to [[Holocaust]] survivor parents.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://ausink.wordpress.com/2011/05/18/a-golem-story-interview/ |title=A Golem Story (interview with Yael Stone) |date=18 May 2011 |publisher=}}</ref> Yael's father is from a [[Jewish]] family, whereas her mother [[Conversion to Judaism|converted to Judaism]].<ref name=profile>{{Cite web |title=The 'kooky' life of Orange Is the New Black's Yael Stone |first=Michaela |last=McGuire |work=[[The Saturday Paper]] |date=2 May 2015 |accessdate=24 August 2015 |url=https://www.thesaturdaypaper.com.au/culture/theatre/2015/05/02/the-kooky-life-orange-the-new-blacks-yael-stone/14304888001814}}</ref><ref>[http://www.westcoastsentinel.com.au/story/4198720/id-rather-be-invisible-orange-is-the-new-black-star-yael-stone-speaks-about-stardom/?cs=36 'I'd rather be invisible': Orange is the New Black star Yael Stone speaks about stardom | West Coast Sentinel<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> Her brother, Jake Stone, was the lead singer of the band [[Bluejuice]]. Her sister, [[Elana Stone]], is also a musician.<ref name=vogue/>

Stone attended the [[Newtown High School of the Performing Arts]] and the [[National Institute of Dramatic Art]] (NIDA).<ref name=chron>{{cite web |url=http://www.thechronicle.com.au/news/aussie-actor-yael-stone-had-just-a-handful-of-cred/2071209 |title=Yael Stone takes lead in Orange is the New Black |date=2 November 2013 |work=[[The Toowoomba Chronicle]] |first=Seanna |last=Cronin |accessdate=25 April 2014}}</ref>

==Career==
Stone began acting as a child, with roles in the film ''[[Me Myself I (film)|Me Myself I]]'' and the miniseries ''The Farm''.<ref name=vogue>{{cite web |url=http://www.vogue.com.au/culture/features/actress+yael+stone+bites+the+acting+bullet,16495 |first=Alexandra |last=Spring |title=Actress Yael Stone bites the acting bullet |date=12 December 2011 |work=[[Vogue (magazine)|Vogue Australia]] |accessdate=25 April 2014}}</ref> She worked primarily in theatre; at the 2008 Sydney Theatre Awards, she won the awards for Best Newcomer and Best Supporting Actress for her performance in ''The Kid''.<ref name=smh>{{cite web |url=http://www.smh.com.au/entertainment/theatre/loves-locks-lost-for-brushes-with-lunacy-20110116-19shj.html |first=Catherine |last=Keenan |title=Love's locks lost for brushes with lunacy |date=17 January 2011 |work=[[The Sydney Morning Herald]] |accessdate=25 April 2014}}</ref> She also worked in television, including supporting roles in ''[[All Saints (TV series)|All Saints]]'' and ''[[Spirited]]''.<ref name=vogue/> From 2010 to 2011, she appeared in ''The Diary of a Madman'' (a theatrical adaptation of the [[Nikolai Gogol|Gogol]] [[Diary of a Madman (short story)|short story]]), a role for which she was again nominated for Best Supporting Actress at the Sydney Theatre Awards.<ref name=smh/> In February 2011, she travelled to [[New York City]] to perform in the [[Brooklyn Academy of Music]]'s production of ''The Diary of a Madman'',<ref name=smh/> before returning to lead roles in ''A Golem Story'', ''[[Summer of the Seventeenth Doll]]'', and ''[[As You Like It]]'' in Sydney.<ref name=vogue/>

Stone moved to New York permanently in December 2011 and co-founded an experimental theatre company.<ref name=vogue/> After four months in New York, she was cast in the [[Netflix]] series ''[[Orange Is the New Black]]'', a show set in a women's prison.<ref name=chron/> Stone plays [[Lorna Morello]], a prisoner from [[New Jersey]]; her accent, a mixture of [[Brooklyn accent|Brooklyn]] and [[Boston accent|Boston]],<ref name=Stone>{{cite web |last1=Stone |first1=Jake |title=Yael Stone On Orange Is The New Black, And Trying To Make It In New York |url=http://junkee.com/yael-stone-on-orange-is-the-new-black-and-trying-to-making-it-in-new-york/16389 |website=Junkee |publisher=Junkee.com |accessdate=8 June 2014 |date=8 May 2013}}</ref> was called "the most amazing accent on television" by a journalist for ''[[The New Republic]]'',<ref>{{cite web |url=https://newrepublic.com/article/114440/orange-new-black-lornas-accent-interview-yael-stone |title=Meet the Australian Actress Who Does the Most Amazing Accent on Television |date=23 August 2013 |first=Laura |last=Bennett |work=[[The New Republic]] |accessdate=25 April 2014}}</ref> while another reviewer deemed the role to be Stone's "breakout turn".<ref name=if>{{cite web |url=http://if.com.au/2013/07/15/article/Orange-is-the-New-Black-for-Yael-Stone/XWXETKBKCH.html |date=15 July 2013 |title=Orange is the New Black for Yael Stone |first=Don |last=Groves |work=IF Magazine |accessdate=25 April 2014}}</ref> She reprised her role in the show's second season,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://au.news.yahoo.com/thewest/a/19703304/breakout-role-for-aussie-yael-stone/ |first=Holly |last=Richards |date=6 November 2013 |title=Breakout role for Aussie Yael Stone |work=[[The West Australian]] |accessdate=25 April 2014}}</ref> and was billed as a series regular in the third season.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.deadline.com/2014/06/yael-stone-upped-to-regular-orange-is-the-new-black-jonathan-adams-last-man-standing/ |first=Nellie |last=Andreeva |date=6 November 2013 |title=Yael Stone Upped To Regular On ‘Orange’, Jonathan Adams On ‘Last Man Standing’ |website=[[Deadline Hollywood]] |accessdate=14 June 2014}}</ref>

She has also appeared on the HBO and web series ''[[High Maintenance]]''.

==Personal life==
In 2012, Stone married Australian actor [[Dan Spielman]], with whom she lived in [[New York City]].<ref name=if/> In July 2017, Stone announced that her marriage had ended over a year before.<ref name="twitter">{{cite web |url=https://twitter.com/yaelstone/status/883025580278546432 |title=For the record; my marriage ended a year ago. An awkward but necessary clarification. I've got amazing people by my side and ❤️ in my heart. |last=Stone |first=Yael |work=Twitter |date=6 July 2017 |accessdate=6 July 2017}}</ref> Stone is an [[atheist]].<ref name="thegloss">{{cite web |url=http://www.thegloss.com/culture/yael-stone-childhoods-end-orange-is-the-new-black-interview/ |title=<i>Orange is the New Black</i>’s Yael Stone Explores <i>Childhood’s End</i> |date=11 December 2015 |publisher=}}</ref> Stone is currently dating AIME Mentoring founder Jack Manning Bancroft. On 23 November 2017, it was announced they are expecting their first child.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.chillifm.com.au/entertainment/best-of-the-web/104679-actress-yael-stone-expecting-first-baby |title=Actress Yael Stone expecting first baby |last=chillifm.com.au |website=www.chillifm.com.au |language=en-gb |access-date=1 December 2017}}</ref> On 30 May 2018, they welcomed a baby girl, Pemau Stone Bancroft.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://popculture.com/celebrity-moms/2018/06/15/oitnb-star-yael-stone-jack-manning-bancroft-welcome-baby-girl/ |title='Orange Is the New Black' Star Welcomes Baby Girl |work=Celebrity Moms |access-date=15 June 2018 |language=en}}</ref>

On 16 December 2018, ''[[The New York Times]]'' published an interview with Stone, who accused Australian actor [[Geoffrey Rush]] of sexual misconduct during the production of ''The Diary of a Madman'' in 2010 and 2011. She alleged that he had sent her inappropriate texts that were "sexual in nature", had touched her back in an "unwanted and sustained" manner at an awards show, had held a mirror above her shower cubicle while she was showering, and had danced naked in front of her in their dressing room.<ref>{{cite web|first=Bari|last=Weiss|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/12/16/opinion/metoo-defamation-geoffrey-rush-yael-stone.html|title=The Cost of Telling a #MeToo Story in Australia|publisher=New York Times|date=16 December 2018|accessdate=17 December 2018}}</ref>

